<h2>Supervision Statement (English)</h2>

<p>I am Alexander Kilpatrick, Director of the Language, Cognition, and Computation Lab at the University of Aizu. This page outlines my approach to supervising graduate theses and what students can expect when working with me.</p>

<h3>Approach to Supervision</h3>
<p>I believe that a large part of the learning process is independent thought and study, so I try not to be too hands‑on. I encourage students to develop their own ideas and drive their research forward, while I provide guidance on direction, methodology, and academic rigour.</p>

<h3>Availability</h3>
<p>I make a point of being highly available to my students. I respond to emails promptly and keep my calendar open for meetings. My lab meets every Wednesday, and I am always present during periods 5 & 6 (13:20–15:00) if you have questions or need feedback.</p>

<h3>Expectations</h3>
<p>I expect my students to be ambitious. I expect them to do real science: discovering new things and explaining those things to the world. Students should actively explore dissemination opportunities, including both domestic and international conferences and publications.</p>

<h3>Authorship and Publishing</h3>
<p>It is my firm belief that named authors on a paper must have made a significant intellectual contribution, and the determination of that contribution should be made by the first author. In other words, you are <strong>not</strong> required to put my name on your research. I will offer my name only when my input has substantially shaped the work, and the decision rests with the student as first author.</p>

